5.5 Computer Art AI
(The term “AI-Assisted” was chosen because, in this category, artificial intelligence serves as a supportive and enhancing tool rather than the primary creator. Core elements such as concept development, composition, stylistic decisions, editing, and overall artistic direction remain driven by human creativity.
Alternative terms such as AI-Generated, AI-Driven, and AI-Based were considered less accurate:

AI-Generated implies that the work is created entirely by AI;
AI-Driven suggests that AI is the main force directing the project;
AI-Based indicates that the project is fundamentally built on AI technology.
Compared to these options, AI-Assisted most accurately reflects the collaborative nature of human creativity supported by AI tools.
The term “Visual Communication” was selected because it naturally unites two distinct creative fields—Animation (including 2D, 3D, and motion work) and Graphic Design—under one professional domain. Both areas share a common purpose: to convey ideas, meaning, and emotion through visual expression. “Visual Communication” precisely describes this shared foundation and allows both categories to be evaluated fairly within a unified framework.)

Computer Art AI includes visual works created with the support of artificial intelligence tools as part of the creative process. This category focuses on two accepted formats:
AI-Assisted Animation and AI-Assisted Graphic Design.
AI must be used meaningfully in each project, while the core artistic decisions, composition, and final refinement must remain the student's own work.

You may use any creative software such as Photoshop, Illustrator, Blender, After Effects, etc.
Animations should not exceed 5 minutes. Artwork should communicate a clear idea or message.

Registration Requirements

To participate, submit the following:

A video presentation of your project (upload to YouTube and share the link)
Detailed information about your project, including how AI was used
Full participant information
Time spent on the project and the programs/tools used
Judging Criteria

Your work will be evaluated on these aspects:

1. Visual Quality
Explanation: Your artwork or animation should be visually coherent, polished, and well-composed, with thoughtful use of color, layout, and style.
Tip: Focus on clarity, balance, and detail to strengthen the overall visual impact.
2. Impact and Message
Explanation: The work should express a clear idea or emotion and leave a meaningful impression on the viewer.
Tip: Consider what story or message you want to convey, and use visual elements to reinforce it.
3. Originality and Creativity
Explanation: Judges will look for fresh ideas, unique visual approaches, and creative use of AI tools.
Tip: Explore inventive concepts and avoid overly common themes or styles.
4. AI Integration
Explanation: AI must be used responsibly and purposefully. The project should show a balanced combination of AI assistance and the participant’s own creative contribution.
Tip: Clearly demonstrate what AI generated and what you refined, designed, or created manually.
5. Technical Skills
Explanation: This criterion evaluates how effectively you use digital tools—such as layering, motion, effects, or 3D/2D techniques—to enhance your final piece.
Tip: Highlight your technical strengths and ensure the final output is clean and professional.
6. Oral Presentation
Explanation: You must explain your process, show how AI was used, and describe your artistic decisions.
Tip: Practice presenting confidently and clearly.
7. Stand Design
Explanation: Your display should support and elevate the theme of your work, helping the audience understand your concept.
Tip: Arrange your stand thoughtfully to highlight key elements of your project.
Presentation Requirements

Projects must be presented in two stages:

1. Stands
Set up a display of your artwork for review.

2. Presentation for the Jury
Each team member must be present for the presentation.
Teams have 10 minutes for the presentation and 5 minutes for Q&A.

Please prepare all necessary materials in advance (computers, chargers, booklets, etc.).

Important Notes

Rules are subject to change.
Projects from previous years or past competitions will not be accepted.
Fully AI-generated works without meaningful author input will not be accepted.


5.6. Short Movie

The Short Movie category focuses on creating a complete visual story using moving images and sound. The purpose of this category is to assess participants’ abilities in filmmaking, including shooting, directing, and editing a short film. Submitted works must demonstrate a clear narrative structure and solid technical quality in both production and post-production.

Submission of music videos, social media clips, social experiments, or similar formats is strictly prohibited.

Priority Topics

Films created based on the topics listed below will be given priority consideration by the jury. Films based on other topics may still advance and receive awards, however, they will not be eligible for First Place.

The Future of AI in Everyday Life
Balancing Tradition and Modernity
Living with AI Companions
Burnout Generation
Misunderstanding between youth and elders
Reclaiming native language
The cost of appearing successful
Old customs in modern contexts
Identity beyond social media
Life beyond grades and rankings.
Submission Requirements

Upload         a 3–5 minute short film, created entirely by the team, to YouTube, including a brief description.
The film must include:
A pen and a notebook         visible on screen
The spoken phrase “Excuse me”
The exact timestamp of this moment must be specified in the video description.        
Submit         a behind-the-scenes (backstage) video         (2–3 minutes maximum), showing the filming process.
The backstage video must include photos or footage with the names of all team members who participated in the production.
The filming process must be clearly visible.        
Originality and Eligibility

Submitting films from previous         years or films not created by the registered team is strictly prohibited. Violation of this rule will result in immediate disqualification, and no team member will be allowed to participate in other teams.        
The submitted film must be an original work. While inspiration from existing works is allowed, direct copying is prohibited. The script, concept, and final film must be created exclusively by the team.

Judging Criteria

Films will be evaluated based on the following criteria:

Ability         to develop a complete, coherent, and engaging script
Video         shooting skills         (camera work, framing, stability)
Video         and audio editing quality, including:
Timing         and pacing
Color correction
Exposure and lighting
Sound         quality and sound effects
Originality and creativity
Relevance and engagement of the chosen topic
Stand Presentation (Stand Check)
1. Concept & Message — 25 points

The following aspects are evaluated:

Originality of the idea
Depth and clarity of meaning
Clarity of the message conveyed
Relevance to the contest theme
2. Storytelling & Script — 20 points

The evaluation is based on:

Logical structure of the story
Presence of a clear beginning, development, and conclusion
Dramatic progression and pacing
Overall         coherence of the narrative
3. Directing & Creativity — 15 points

Judges assess:

Authorial vision and creative approach
Use of original and non-standard solutions
Effective use of visual language
Ability         to express ideas through cinematic techniques
4. Acting / Character Development — 15 points

The following are evaluated:

Credibility and authenticity of characters
Emotional expression, facial expressions, and body language
Consistency of performances with the storyline
5. Technical Quality — 15 points

Judges consider:

Image and video quality
Sound quality (dialogue, music, ambient sound)
Editing and transitions
Overall         technical accuracy and polish
6. Impact & Emotional Effect — 10 points

The evaluation focuses on:

Emotional impact on the audience
Memorability of the film
Ability         to provoke reflection or discussion after viewing































5.7. Arduino Hackathon: Robot Football


Robotics Hackathon is a robotics competition in the robot football format. Teams build two robots based on the ESP32 38pin and compete in 2 vs 2 matches.





1. Participant Selection


Stage 1: Video Presentation


Teams upload a presentation video to YouTube and send the link to the registration platform.


What to show in the video:

Experience in assembling similar robots
Ability to work with ESP32 38pin, ZK5AD driver, and motors
Stage 2: Final


Based on the video assessment, 10 finalist teams are selected and invited to the in-person competition.






2. Team


Composition: 3 participants + 1 mentor (teacher)


Roles during the match:

2 participants — operators (control the robots)
1 participant — substitute/strategist (can be changed)
Mentor:

Can only assist before the competition
Assistance is prohibited during the competition
Important:

Only participants design, build, and program the robots
It is allowed to use AI and the Internet
Organizers will ask questions about the code and prompts — you need to understand and explain your implementation


3. Robot


Requirements


Each team builds 2 robots. The maximum dimensions of one robot are 20 × 30 × 20 cm (width × length × height). 5 hours are given for assembly. Control is via Bluetooth or WiFi (built into the ESP32 38pin).


Mechanisms


Allowed:

Kicker (striking mechanism)
Mini-claws up to 2 cm (only brief grabbing for striking/passing)
Bumper for pushing the ball
Prohibited:

Holding the ball for more than 3 seconds
Lifting the ball above the field
Taking the ball inside the robot
Blocking or damaging opponent's robots





